                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Ab hoc f&egrave;re Persei bello, et &AElig;milij Pauli de maximo rege triumpho, orditur Velleij Paterculi historia. In cuius primo 
                        libro, hi quatuor egregij viri; P. Aemilius, Q. Metellus, Scipio &AElig;milianus, L. Mummius. Secundus liber &agrave; bello Viriathi,
                        et Numantino, ad Tiberij usq[ue] imperium; cui effusius blanditur: pra[e]clarus alioqui historicus, et diligenti animadversione dignus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Perseus"/>
                <person name="Paulus Aemilius Veronensis"/>
                <person name="Marcus Velleius Paterculus"/>
                <person name="Quintus Caecilius Metellus Macedonicus"/> <!-- LS, 3 with similar names on list. Have I chosen the correct one? -->
                <person name="Scipio Aemilianus"/>
                <person name="Lucius Mummius Achaicus"/>
                <person name="Viriatus Lusitanus"/>
                <person name="Tiberius"/> <!-- LS, 3 with similar names on list. Have I chosen the correct one? -->
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Approximately from this war of Perseus and Aemilius Paulusâ€™ victory over the greatest king, commences the history of Velleius Paterculus. 
                In his first book appear these four extraordinary men: Publius Aemilius Paullus, Quintus Metellus, Scipio Aemilianus and Lucius Mummius. 
                The second book [covers the period] from the war of Viriathus and the Numantine war to the rule of Tiberius, whom he flatters rather 
                immoderately; else a brilliant historian and worth careful attention.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
